comment:
1, A. Myth; 
Whilst there may have been a person leading a Jewish cult that may even have been excuted, none of the miracles have any basis in fact.
2, A. Myth;
Complete fabrication.
The NT was compiled in the late 4th Century AD, being criticised at the time for the overtly political choice of which texts were included as Canon and which were rejected to become the Apocrypha. Further it is now generally accepted that the text was altered at a later date to comply with OT prophesy. 
Like The Saxon Chronicles, King Arthur or Robin Hood there is too much romanticisation and mythologising to be certain of virtually anything in the text.

Just so there isn't any more confusion on the matter the texts I am refering to are listed here;
http://www.comparative-religion.com/...ent-apocrypha/
The initial date I gave refers to the Vulgate and the work of St. Jerome under the direction of Pope Damasus I, it would appear that the start point of establishing a canon for the NT goes back to around 150AD and is attributed to Marcion of Sinope.
